  "slug": "chicken-pathia",
  "title": "Chicken pathia",
  "subtitle": "Sweet, sour, and hot, the Persian-Parsi triple",
  "excerpt": "Chicken pieces in a thick, dark sauce that balances three competing elements: heat from chilli, sweetness from sugar, and sourness from tamarind. Pathia uses the same Parsi flavour architecture as dhansak but without the lentils, a cleaner, more concentrated sauce that coats the chicken and stains it deeply. Ordered for its distinctive triple-contrast character.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pathia (also patio) is a Parsi dish of Persian origin, a thick sweet-sour-hot sauce traditionally eaten with fish or meat. In the British curry-house it is typically made with chicken and ordered as an alternative to madras by diners who want heat alongside sweet-sour complexity.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pathia is a balancing act: the three elements (sweet, sour, hot) need to be in tension with each other, not one dominating. Add the tamarind, then taste. Add the sugar, then taste again. They should counteract without cancelling. If the sauce tastes sweet, add more tamarind. If it tastes too sour, add more sugar. The heat from the chilli should be felt after swallowing, not immediately on the palate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The sauce must be reduced until it is very thick and almost jammy before the chicken is returned. This concentration is what makes pathia different from a simple sweet-sour curry, the sauce clings to the chicken rather than surrounding it as a liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
