        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the sauce base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over high heat. Brown the {{chicken-thighs-boneless}} in batches for 2 minutes per side. Remove and set aside. Reduce the heat to medium. Add the {{onion}} and cook for 12 minutes until deep golden. Add the {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{turmeric}}, {{cumin-ground}}, {{coriander-ground}}, and {{chilli-powder}} and stir for 1 minute. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}} and cook for 10 minutes, stirring frequently, until reduced to a thick paste.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Balance the sauce and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the {{tamarind-paste}} and {{brown-sugar}} to the tomato paste. Stir well and taste, adjust the balance so both sour and sweet are present. Add 200 ml water and bring to a simmer. Return the chicken and cook for 20 minutes until cooked through and the sauce is thick and clinging. Stir in the {{garam-masala}} and season with salt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Taste at the stage before the chicken is returned. Add tamarind or sugar in small amounts until both are detectable but neither dominates",
              "cause": "Sweet-sour balance off",
              "symptom": "One element dominates"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Simmer uncovered and stir frequently until the sauce thickens to coat the back of a spoon heavily",
              "cause": "Not reduced enough at the tomato-paste stage",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Thigh meat is better for this dish. It tolerates the long sauce reduction without drying. Reduce cooking time for breast pieces",
              "cause": "Overcooked or breast meat used",
              "symptom": "Chicken dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a pinch more at the end, pathia should be hot, sitting in the same bracket as madras",
              "cause": "Chilli powder variation",
              "symptom": "Heat not prominent"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pathia is a regular on British curry-house menus though less commonly ordered than tikka masala or korma. It rewards diners who want something more complex than a standard hot curry. The sweet-sour-hot triad is a Parsi cooking principle that appears in multiple dishes; pathia is its cleanest expression on the British Indian menu. It is worth ordering with plain rice rather than pilau, so the sauce flavour is not competing with spiced rice.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
